{"name":"Poisoned","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.eJQ3ve6RTdjbNGEz"}},"pages":[{"name":"Poisoned","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<ul>\n<li>A poisoned creature has disadvantage on attack rolls and ability checks.</li>\n</ul>"},"_id":"iebFSXvQ66TM2mLF","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546490,"modifiedTime":1670762848882,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"2E3Uraw4EpRQddcl","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Cleanse","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.0BZaRbnl3LzlTJQL"}},"pages":[{"name":"Cleanse","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>A creature of evil alignment that comes under the effect of the cleanse condition feels an agonizing sense of burning in the area affected as well as a white steam can be seen emanating from them.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The Cleansed condition can be applied with holy substances such as holy water, holy fire and the likes. In addition, when a creature with Good alignment deals <strong>radiant</strong> damage to an Evil creature, and the damage is equal to 30% or greater of the Evil creature's maximum hit points, the damaged creature comes under the effect of the cleanse condition.</li>\n<li>A creature with this condition has disadvantage on all attack rolls and ability checks.</li>\n<li>A ccreature with this condition takes <strong>[[/r 1d6]] radiant</strong> damage at the start of each of its turns.</li>\n<li>The Cleansed condition lasts for [[/r 1d4]] rounds.</li>\n<li>Creatures that are not of Evil alignments are immune to this condition.</li>\n</ul>"},"_id":"yzWAiQIZfgZtxNqX","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546482,"modifiedTime":1670762848866,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"4iaBWKkhBpckTeq8","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Prone","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.ekm4TUHKT3QUPdPv"}},"pages":[{"name":"Prone","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<ul>\n<li>A prone creature's only movement option is to crawl, unless it stands up and thereby ends the condition.</li>\n<li>The creature has disadvantage on attack rolls.</li>\n<li>An attack roll against the creature has advantage if the attacker is within 5 feet of the creature. Otherwise, the attack roll has disadvantage.</li>\n</ul>"},"_id":"xKNumCwDUuzG20Ab","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546490,"modifiedTime":1670762848882,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"57oKUOZZK6m3WGIK","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Paralyzed","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.o5oZVdHSWmceeFyx"}},"pages":[{"name":"Paralyzed","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<ul>\n<li>A paralyzed creature is @Compendium[SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.hWk0QM9u7SUpd4BX]{Incapacitated} and can't move or speak.</li>\n<li>The creature automatically fails Strength and Dexterity saving throws. Attack rolls against the creature have advantage.</li>\n<li>Any attack that hits the creature is a critical hit if the attacker is within 5 feet of the creature.</li>\n</ul>"},"_id":"OrAqBpB3ca5NbDQI","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546492,"modifiedTime":1670762848884,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"72lzh6FBYIjFQb7B","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Stunned","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.IDLJEkgkdcnljtEW"}},"pages":[{"name":"Stunned","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<ul>\n<li>A stunned creature is @Compendium[SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.hWk0QM9u7SUpd4BX]{Incapacitated}, can't move, and can speak only falteringly.</li>\n<li>The creature automatically fails Strength and Dexterity saving throws.</li>\n<li>Attack rolls against the creature have advantage.</li>\n</ul>"},"_id":"nFiFL1uLvebi5JDp","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546485,"modifiedTime":1670762848873,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"8qqw0rWZ9jNcNBux","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Frightened","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.PTANb5kCweCv3Jna"}},"pages":[{"name":"Frightened","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<ul>\n<li>A frightened creature has disadvantage on ability checks and attack rolls while the source of its fear is within line of sight.</li>\n<li>The creature can't willingly move closer to the source of its fear.</li>\n</ul>"},"_id":"4WZZ40O0CvI3RWxT","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546486,"modifiedTime":1670762848876,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"9TeoG69qysUc4EMx","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Muted","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.UloDY1dagGwD43Id"}},"pages":[{"name":"Muted","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<ul>\n<li>A muted creature cannot communicate verbally, nor cast spells with a verbal component.</li>\n</ul>"},"_id":"wB6O36lDnATDI6NJ","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546490,"modifiedTime":1670762848881,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"9XoRbplU5SP0UxHi","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Exhaustion","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.4Z1Ins4wHUAWJal2"}},"pages":[{"name":"Exhaustion","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>Some special abilities and environmental hazards, such as starvation and the long-term effects of freezing or scorching temperatures, can lead to a special condition called exhaustion. Exhaustion is measured in six levels. An effect can give a creature one or more levels of exhaustion, as specified in the effect's description.</p>\n<table style=\"height:119px\" border=\"1\">\n<tbody>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:67px;height:17px;text-align:center\"><strong>Level</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width:600px;height:17px\"><strong>Effect</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:67px;height:17px;text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"width:600px;height:17px\">Disadvantage on ability checks</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:67px;height:17px;text-align:center\">2</td>\n<td style=\"width:600px;height:17px\">Speed halved</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:67px;height:17px;text-align:center\">3</td>\n<td style=\"width:600px;height:17px\">Disadvantage on attack rolls and saving throws</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:67px;height:17px;text-align:center\">4</td>\n<td style=\"width:600px;height:17px\">Hit point maximum halved</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:67px;height:17px;text-align:center\">5</td>\n<td style=\"width:600px;height:17px\">Speed reduced to 0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:67px;height:17px;text-align:center\">6</td>\n<td style=\"width:600px;height:17px\">Death</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p> </p>\n<p>If an already exhausted creature suffers another effect that causes exhaustion, its current level of exhaustion increases by the amount specified in the effect's description.</p>\n<p>A creature suffers the effect of its current level of exhaustion as well as all lower levels. For example, a creature suffering level 2 exhaustion has its speed halved and has disadvantage on ability checks.</p>\n<p>An effect that removes exhaustion reduces its level as specified in the effect's description, with all exhaustion effects ending if a creature's exhaustion level is reduced below 1.</p>\n<p>Finishing a long rest reduces a creature's exhaustion level by 1, provided that the creature has also ingested some food and drink. Also, being raised from the dead reduces a creature’s exhaustion level by 1.</p>"},"_id":"K6ohnaxw9seRP3LP","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546485,"modifiedTime":1670762848872,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"EdBydhE6hvbxbjYp","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Invisible","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.pSvtps6WHVAuWh9l"}},"pages":[{"name":"Invisible","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<ul>\n<li>An invisible creature is impossible to see without the aid of magic or a special sense. For the purpose of hiding, the creature is heavily obscured. The creature's location can be detected by any noise it makes or any tracks it leaves.</li>\n<li>Attack rolls against the creature have disadvantage, and the creature's attack rolls have advantage.</li>\n</ul>"},"_id":"GeM1V3Gv04PMSRsg","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546492,"modifiedTime":1670762848885,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"GCo74LHqzZX40mGm","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Charmed","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.UWlXFfSX95JVWrYs"}},"pages":[{"name":"Charmed","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<ul>\n<li>A charmed creature can't attack the charmer or target the charmer with harmful abilities or magical effects.</li>\n<li>The charmer has advantage on any ability check to interact socially with the creature.</li>\n</ul>"},"_id":"PVE23rEgsQHBi98Z","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546490,"modifiedTime":1670762848881,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"Jsqrugg2SOlLQKT8","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Restrained","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.0mkU8eksNfwd1AZY"}},"pages":[{"name":"Restrained","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<ul>\n<li>A restrained creature's speed becomes 0, and it can't benefit from any bonus to its speed.</li>\n<li>Attack rolls against the creature have advantage, and the creature's attack rolls have disadvantage.</li>\n<li>The creature has disadvantage on Dexterity saving throws.</li>\n</ul>"},"_id":"bvAU1bdE1PugbyQ2","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546482,"modifiedTime":1670762848868,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"L6bDHoucx7hXKgY7","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Maimed","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.JUlS7g20oV6yRs3A"}},"pages":[{"name":"Maimed","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>At the DM's descretion, particularly painful traps and monsters that maim their prey can cause the Maimed condition.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>When a Maimed creature takes damage for the first time each round, it loses [[1d6]] hit points.</li>\n<li>A Maimed creature has disadvantage on <strong>Constitution</strong>, <strong>Dexterity</strong>, and <strong>Strength</strong> saving throws and ability checks.</li>\n<li>When a Maimed creature would regain hit points, it doesn’t, and the maimed condition ends.</li>\n</ul>"},"_id":"Jn5aSIEDOD6PBanv","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546485,"modifiedTime":1670762848874,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"SpKjlsdsFZlNaQxz","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Blinded","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.oScVqOHJt5SQszVl"}},"pages":[{"name":"Blinded","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<ul>\n<li>A blinded creature can't see and automatically fails any ability check that requires sight.</li>\n<li>Attack rolls against the creature have advantage, and the creature's attack rolls have disadvantage.</li>\n</ul>"},"_id":"nz1oEjowOMZZ5vBx","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546492,"modifiedTime":1670762848885,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"Xb9bT3rUXjpaffEj","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Petrified","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.KaKNDyLeWRGqpBlc"}},"pages":[{"name":"Petrified","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<ul>\n<li>A petrified creature is transformed, along with any nonmagical object it is wearing or carrying, into a solid inanimate substance (usually stone). Its weight increases by a factor of ten, and it ceases aging.</li>\n<li>The creature is @Compendium[SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.hWk0QM9u7SUpd4BX]{Incapacitated}, can't move or speak, and is unaware of its surroundings.</li>\n<li>Attack rolls against the creature have advantage.</li>\n<li>The creature automatically fails <strong>Strength </strong>and <strong>Dexterity </strong>saving throws.</li>\n<li>The creature has resistance to all damage.</li>\n<li>The creature is immune to <strong>poison </strong>and <strong>disease</strong>, although a poison or disease already in its system is suspended, not neutralized.</li>\n</ul>"},"_id":"43lqkKjuPznycp8e","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546486,"modifiedTime":1670762848874,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"XzFW9WUHyiwQb0lz","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Grappled","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.qKqW3LJEQpJ7T3v8"}},"pages":[{"name":"Grappled","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<ul>\n<li>A grappled creature's speed becomes 0, and it can't benefit from any bonus to its speed.</li>\n<li>The condition ends if the grappler is @Compendium[SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.hWk0QM9u7SUpd4BX]{Incapacitated}.</li>\n<li>The condition also ends if an effect removes the grappled creature from the reach of the grappler or grappling effect, such as when a creature is hurled away by the thunderwave spell.</li>\n</ul>"},"_id":"XSeuBmdpOXT2vNRK","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546493,"modifiedTime":1670762848886,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"fo4uvSqiTlLewSHN","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Concentrating","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.nSoKejZfahbxfggp"}},"pages":[{"name":"Concentrating","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>Some spells require you to maintain concentration in order to keep their magic active. If you lose concentration, such a spell ends.</p>\n<p>If a spell must be maintained with concentration, that fact appears in its Duration entry, and the spell specifies how long you can concentrate on it. You can end concentration at any time (no action required).</p>\n<p>Normal activity, such as moving and attacking, doesn't interfere with concentration. The following factors can break concentration:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Casting another spell that requires concentration.</strong> You lose concentration on a spell if you cast another spell that requires concentration. You can't concentrate on two spells at once.</li>\n<li><strong>Taking damage. </strong>Whenever you take damage while you are concentrating on a spell, you must make a Constitution saving throw to maintain your concentration. The DC equals 10 or half the damage you take, whichever number is higher. If you take damage from multiple sources, such as an arrow and a dragon's breath, you make a separate saving throw for each source of damage.</li>\n<li><strong>Being incapacitated or killed.</strong> You lose concentration on a spell if you are @Compendium[SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.hWk0QM9u7SUpd4BX]{Incapacitated} or if you die.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The DM might also decide that certain environmental phenomena, such as a wave crashing over you while you're on a storm-tossed ship, require you to succeed on a <strong>DC 10 Constitution saving throw</strong> to maintain concentration on a spell.</p>"},"_id":"yII4pTpjtKcP8rfN","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546491,"modifiedTime":1670762848883,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"hutyCTSzw2ZFIyCn","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Intoxicated","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.M3CEleQiXm7Mlt1O"}},"pages":[{"name":"Intoxicated","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>An intoxicated creature is drunk, usually from drinking too much alcohol or from being poisoned.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>An intoxicated creature has disadvantage on <strong>Dexterity</strong>, <strong>Wisdom</strong>, and <strong>Intelligence </strong>ability checks and saving throws, as well as attack rolls.</li>\n<li>An intoxicated creature has advantage on <strong>Charisma</strong> ability checks.</li>\n<li>An intoxicated creature gains temporary hit points equal to their level + 5 for the duration of the condition.</li>\n<li>Every time an intoxicated creature fails a <strong>Constitution saving throw</strong> to resist further intoxication, they gain 1 level of exhaustion.</li>\n<li>Every hour while they are conscious and intoxicated, or if they are conscious and have levels of exhaustion caused by inxotication, the creature must make a <strong>Constitution saving throw</strong> (DC = 10 + levels of exhaustion). If they succeed and they have levels of exhaustion caused by this condition, a level of exhaustion is removed. If they succeed and don't have levels of exhaustion caused by this condition, they are no longer intoxicated.</li>\n<li>This condition also ends when the creature finishes a long rest.</li>\n</ul>"},"_id":"q5cRDjPmn1EnV6eZ","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546486,"modifiedTime":1670762848875,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"mGiWKU1CUhzYM7yB","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Frozen","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.R0L6X2Ra64UKlMSI"}},"pages":[{"name":"Frozen","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>A creature that has contact with extreme cold might become frozen. </p>\n<ul>\n<li>When a creature takes <strong>cold damage</strong> that is equal to more than 30% of their max hit points, they become frozen.</li>\n<li>When a creature is frozen, their speed is reduced to zero, and if they remain in this condition for more than 3 turns, they take <strong>[[/r 1d6]] cold</strong> damage for every turn they remain frozen past the third.</li>\n<li>Any creature affiliated with fire (such as magma mephitis, fire elementals, red dragons, etc) are immune to this condition.</li>\n<li>A creature immune to cold damage is immune to this condition.</li>\n</ul>"},"_id":"oEkjMnL4jDuHnh88","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546487,"modifiedTime":1670762848876,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"oVOWVWvfybfYS4VV","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Flying","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.RhOz43NCZ4WtgWsh"}},"pages":[{"name":"Flying","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>Flying creatures enjoy many benefits of mobility, but they must also deal with the danger of falling. If a flying creature is knocked @Compendium[SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.ekm4TUHKT3QUPdPv]{Prone}, has its speed reduced to 0, or is otherwise deprived of the ability to move, the creature falls, unless it has the ability to hover or it is being held aloft by magic, such as by the fly spell.</p>"},"_id":"tPNZ6RLlx8SBr79M","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546487,"modifiedTime":1670762848878,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"opsDnaGGwp4FOFev","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Deafened","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.p9CQYqWS7s4Abwqk"}},"pages":[{"name":"Deafened","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<ul>\n<li>A deafened creature can't hear and automatically fails any ability check that requires hearing.</li>\n</ul>"},"_id":"9vETg7VzDceDKPC4","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546492,"modifiedTime":1670762848885,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"q3V6CVBXLWefZGJo","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Spasmic","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.u7r3QfFuBx4EfVcK"}},"pages":[{"name":"Spasmic","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<ul>\n<li>The creature is overcome with shaking and cannot take bonus actions or reactions.</li>\n<li>It has disadvantage on Strength and Dexterity saving throws, checks, and all attack rolls that use either ability.</li>\n</ul>"},"_id":"yDWTLzyNpmFDuoLG","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546493,"modifiedTime":1670762848886,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"t4Ri11BThcB6NsoX","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Unconscious","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.S499QUmXTVx81wk8"}},"pages":[{"name":"Unconscious","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<ul>\n<li>An unconscious creature is @Compendium[SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.hWk0QM9u7SUpd4BX]{Incapacitated}, can't move or speak, and is unaware of its surroundings.</li>\n<li>The creature drops whatever it's holding and falls @Compendium[SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.ekm4TUHKT3QUPdPv]{Prone}.</li>\n<li>The creature automatically fails Strength and Dexterity saving throws.</li>\n<li>Attack rolls against the creature have advantage.</li>\n<li>Any attack that hits the creature is a critical hit if the attacker is within 5 feet of the creature.</li>\n</ul>"},"_id":"GsmGBygvpD4ep9me","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546487,"modifiedTime":1670762848878,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"vqUvhaxDYjnvaPr6","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Burned","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.Si08jyNRYuG8devu"}},"pages":[{"name":"Burned","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>A creature that comes under the effect of the Burned condition takes one of the three degrees of this condition based on the amount of fire damage they took compared to their maximum hit points. When you take a degree of Burned you take all lower degrees of burn. <em>For example, if you had 100 hit points and you took 51 fire damage you would be affected by the effects of Second degree as well as First degree.</em></p>\n<table border=\"1\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:84.6667px\"><strong>Degree</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width:613.333px\"><strong>Effect</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:84.6667px\">First (25%)</td>\n<td style=\"width:613.333px\">Your skin becomes bright pink or very red. You have disadvantage on your next weapon attack roll. You have disadvantage on Charisma checks.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:84.6667px\">Second (50%)</td>\n<td style=\"width:613.333px\"> Your skin becomes red as blisters begin to form on the affected area. You have disadvantage on Dexterity saving throws and ability checks. Your speed is also halved.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:84.6667px\">Third (75%)</td>\n<td style=\"width:613.333px\">Your skin is seared black as the fire almost overwhelms you. Make a Constitution saving throw, versus the spell save DC or a DC appropriate for the source (DM sets the DC). On a fail, the pain becomes too much to handle and you pass out for 1 hour, falling prone and becoming unconscious. On a successful save, you are not affected. Additionally, if the burned level is decreased, you wake up.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>Magical healing reduces your burned level by one for every 25% of your max hit points it heals. The @Compendium[dnd5e.spells.F0GsG0SJzsIOacwV]{Lesser Restoration} spell can remove one level of this condition, while @Compendium[dnd5e.spells.WzvJ7G3cqvIubsLk]{Greater Restoration} can remove all degrees at once. Finishing a long rest reduces a creature's exhaustion level by one, provided that the creature has also ingested some food and drink.</p>\n<p>Creatures that are<strong> immune to fire damage</strong> are immune to this condition. While creatures that are <strong>resistant to fire damage</strong> require 25% more of their hit point maximum to be affected by a level. For example, if a creature has resistance to fire damage and 50% of its hit point maximum was just taken in fire damage it would have the first degree burned condition.</p>"},"_id":"dD4EVTOa1mFRthv2","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546488,"modifiedTime":1670762848880,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"vuFIr02hgCnFqe0i","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
{"name":"Incapacitated","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.SupersHomebrewPack.conditions.hWk0QM9u7SUpd4BX"}},"pages":[{"name":"Incapacitated","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<ul>\n<li>An incapacitated creature can't take actions or reactions.</li>\n</ul>"},"_id":"cBEayRFBchbgcQ9n","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670762546491,"modifiedTime":1670762848882,"lastModifiedBy":"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa"},"_id":"zVt199tQfn6mMgok","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"xwZ4GUD7p7XTKvqa":3}}
